sensorFilters.label: East Coast Region
sensorFilters.description:
The U.S. East and Gulf Coasts study region extends from 43.7931ºN to 28.9060ºN. The East Coast includes 16 States that border the Atlantic Ocean: Maine, New Hampshire, Massachusetts, Rhode Island, Connecticut, New York, Pennsylvania, New Jersey, Delaware, Maryland, Virginia, North Carolina, South Carolina, Georgia, and the east coast of Florida. The Gulf Coast States include Texas, Louisiana, Mississippi, Alabama, and Florida?s west coast. Extreme waves along the U.S. East and Gulf Coast are dominated by tropical storms and hurricanes during the boreal summer months and extra-tropical storms (also known as Nor?Easters) in boreal fall and winter between October and March. Tropical storms and hurricanes derive energy from a central warm core over the ocean that results in low-pressure systems, strong atmospheric pressure gradients, and extreme high winds that are typically confined to the storm center. In contrast, extra-tropical storms derive their strength from a horizontal temperature gradient originating out from a cold core, with atmospheric pressure gradients and consequent winds extending over large spatial areas. Hurricane winds are often not resolved in coarse model grids such as those of the global climate models used to compute wave conditions in this study and therefore hurricane-related waves are likely not included in the deep water wave computations of this study.

The continental shelf along the U.S. East and Gulfs Coasts are mostly wide (>100 km) and thus expected to provide some dissipation of wave energy prior to waves reaching the shore. Exceptions exist offshore of Cape Hatteras, North Carolina, southeast Florida, and the Mississippi Delta, Louisiana where the shelf narrows to less than 20 km. The coast is characterized by gentle shorelines, dunes, estuaries, and barrier islands much of which are attributed to the rise of eustatic sea level since last glaciation. The East and Gulf Coasts are major centers of economic activity with more than 60 million persons living in coastal counties; the largest coastal populations being in New York and Florida. Oil and gas deposits, combined with easy access to shipping and several thousand oil platforms have made the Gulf Coast a major U.S. petrochemical industry hub. Both the Gulf and Atlantic Coasts host valuable marshlands and lagoon habitats that support extensive fishing industries. Residences, cultural and historic resources, agriculture, ports, tourism, major transportation corridors, and natural resources abut the shore and are routinely battered by coastal storms, resulting in some of the Nation?s costliest natural disasters. The combination of high waves and storm surge combined with rising sea level increases the likelihood that more wave energy will reach exposed stretches of the coast resulting in potentially increased flooding and erosion.

Bibliography

  • Dalyander, P.S., and Butman, B. (2015) ?Characteristics of storms driving wave-induced seafloor mobility on the U.S. East Coast continental shelf?. Continental Shelf Research, 104, 1-14.
  • Marciano, C.G., Lackmann, G.M., and Robinson, W.A. (2014) ?Changes in U.S. East Coast cyclone dynamics with climate change?. J. of Climate, 28, 468-484.
  • McAdie, C.J., Landsea, C.W., Neumann, C.J., David, J.E., Blake, E.S., Hammer, G.R. (2009) ?Tropical Cyclones of the North Atlantic Ocean, 1851?2006?. National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration Historical Climatology Series, 6-2.
  • Melillo, J. (2014) ?Northeast climate change impacts in the United States?. In Horton, R.M., Yohe, G., Fasterling, G., Easterlin, W., Kates, R., Ruth, M., Sussman, E., Whelchel, A., Wolfe, D., and Lipschultz, F., (Eds.) The Third National Climate Assessment, Ch. 16. National Climate Assessment, Washington, D.C., 371-395.
  • National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration, NOAA (2013) ?National Coastal Population Report. Population trends from 1970 to 2020?. Developed in partnership with the U.S Census Bureau. http://stateofthecoast.noaa.gov
  • Zhang, K., Douglas, B.C., Leatherman, S.P. (2000) ?Twentieth-century storm activity along the U.S. East Coast?. J. of Climate, 13(10), 1748?1761.

sensorFilters.label: Alaska Coast Region
sensorFilters.description:
The Alaska coast study region includes the waters of the Beaufort and Chukchi Seas north of the Bering Strait and adjacent to the Arctic North Slope, the Bering Sea off western Alaska, and the North Pacific Ocean off the southern Alaska and Aleutian Island coasts. The Beaufort, Chukchi and Bering Seas are subject to seasonal sea-ice growth and decay that, during the deepest months of boreal winter, covers the entire water surface with ice so that wind wave growth is unable to occur. Sea-ice melt and freeze in the Bering and Chukchi Seas typically occurs in June/July and September/October, respectively. Compared to the Arctic region, the Bering Sea situated just south of and connected to the Chukchi Sea via the Bering Strait, typically experiences seasonal melt and freeze a month to nearly two months earlier and later on each end of the open-water season.

Coastal regions of Alaska are regularly affected by intense storms of ocean origin. Starting in late-July to mid-August, low-pressure cells originating in the Pacific Ocean or Chukchi Sea traverse eastward across Alaska and the Beaufort Sea, bringing with them high winds that can generate high waves in the Chukchi and Beaufort Seas. The most commonly observed storm tracks that reach Western Alaska and the Bering Sea originate in the North Pacific, and to a lesser degree, in the Arctic. North Pacific storms often begin and intensify over the warm western boundary of the Kuroshio Current east of Japan. The other dominant storm track entering the Bering Sea from the south is often linked to the Aleutian Low. The Aleutian Low is a climatic feature of low atmospheric-pressure fields centered near the Aleutian Islands and represents one of the main centers of action in atmospheric circulation of the Northern Hemisphere. While less commonly affecting Bering Sea storminess, cyclones that develop in the Arctic over Siberia are sometimes also steered toward this area. Extreme waves along the southern coast of Alaska are mostly the result of high winds associated with the Aleutian Low and other North Pacific atmospheric cyclones.

The continental shelf extends across nearly half of the Bering Sea, resulting in limited local wave growth and some dissipation of wave energy entering from the south between the Aleutian Islands and from the north through the Bering Strait. While not as wide as in the Bering Sea, the continental shelves along the northern Alaska and most parts of the southern Alaska coast are also wide and thus alter deep water waves prior to reaching the coast. The shores of western and southern Alaska, including the Aleutian Islands, are characterized by high cliffs, gravel beaches, steep and mildly sloping sandy beaches, and many bays and gulfs. Population centers are scattered along both coasts and mostly concentrated near low-lying areas where rivers and streams enter the Bering Sea or Pacific Ocean. The northern Alaska coast is characterized by sand and gravel beaches, barrier islands, thermokarst lakes, bluffs, cliffs, low-lying tundra (often less than 2 m above mean sea level), all in a zone of continuous permafrost; a landscape that is highly susceptible to erosion by wave action and warming air and water temperatures. The North Slope region is an area of active oil exploration and production and, similar to the west and south coasts of Alaska, hosts numerous small Native Villages, irreplaceable cultural resources, and extensive habitat that support a variety of fish, flora, and fauna. Astronomic tides are small along the northern Alaska coast but increase dramatically to the west and south. The coincidence of high waves, high storm surges (more than 3 meters), and in some areas high tides, has resulted in severe coastal erosion and flooding, much of which has gone unreported.

Sea-ice melt and freeze is occurring earlier and later in the year, resulting in extended durations of open water (time when the sea is free of ice). In addition to the extended open water season, total sea ice cover surrounding the Alaska coast has spatially declined. Reductions in sea-ice extent and duration have the potential to increase the frequency and magnitude of high wave events (and storm surges) as larger areas of open water allow for greater regions of wind-sea surface drag, changes in heat storage and release, and changes in atmospheric-ocean interactions. These climate driven changes have the potential to severely increase the vulnerability of exposed populations and habitats to storm-related hazards.

Wave simulation results provided as part of this study were derived using winds from atmosphere-ocean coupled global climate models of which sea ice was included, however, the wave simulations assumed full open water during all months of all years into the 21st century.

Bibliography

  • Atkinson, D.E. (2005) ?Observed storminess patterns and trends in the circum-Arctic coastal regime?. Geo-Mar Letters, 25: 98-109.
  • Cross, A. E. (2010) ?Synoptic drivers of storm surge in Kotzebue Sound?. Thesis for Master of Science, University of Alaska at Fairbanks, 94 pp.
  • Douglas, D.C. (2010) ?Arctic sea ice decline: Projected changes in timing and extent of sea ice in the Bering and Chukchi Seas?. U.S. Geological Survey Open-File Report 2010-1176, 32 p.
  • Francis, O., Panteleev, G.G., and Atkinson, D. E. (2011) ?Ocean wave conditions in the Chukchi Sea from satellite and in situ observations?. Geophysical Research Letters, 38, L24610, 1-5.
  • Hume, J.D. and Schalk, M. (1967) ?Shoreline processes near Barrow, Alaska; a comparison of the normal and the catastrophic?. Arctic, 20(86-103).
  • Lynch, A.H., Cassano, E.N., Cassano, J. J., and Lestak, L. R. (2003) ?Case studies of high wind events in Barrow, Alaska: Climatological context and development processes?. Monthly Weather Review, American Meteorological Society, 131, 719-732.
  • Markus, T., Stroeve, J.C., Miller, J. (2009) ?Recent changes in Arctic sea ice melt onset, freezup, and melt season length?. J. Geophysical Research, 114, C12024, 1-14.
  • Terenzi, J., Torre, J.M., and Ely, C. R. (2014) ?Storm-surge flooding on the Yukon-Kuskokwim Delta, Alaska?. Arctic, 67(3), 360?374.

sensorFilters.label: Fish Counts
sensorFilters.description: The Alaska Department of Fish and Game (ADF&G), federal agencies, and non-government organizations operate counting projects to count the numbers of migrating fish (primarily salmon), using weirs, sonars and counting towers in a number of streams throughout Alaska. The counts are used by the various fisheries divisions for a variety of management objectives.\nThe information displayed has been compiled from the ADF&G Fish Count Data Search website, which contains counts from a number of different sources to provide inseason and historical data. Counts are generated during the summer migration period extending from late-May (when the weir or sonar is installed) until August (when the weir or sonar is removed). The data displayed are daily counts of individual fish passing the count station (i.e. weir, sonar, tower, etc.).  Detailed descriptions of the fish count stations are available through the ADF&G Fish Count Data Search website (see metadata url above).

sensorFilters.label: Global Historical Sensors

Data are from meteorologic and oceanographic observing systems operated by IOOS Regional Associations and local data providers within these regions are represented. Over 35,000 in-situ stations are represented in the map, including weather stations, stream gauges, webcam images, moorings, etc. Measurements include air temperature, air pressure, conductivity, water currents, water level, ground temperature, precipitation, humidity, salinity, snow depth, snow water equivalent, stream flow, stream gauge height, stream temperature, tides, waves, wind, acidity (pH), and more.

These sensor platforms include weather stations, stream gauges, webcam images, moorings, etc. Measurements and predictions compiled from the platforms include air temperature, barometric pressure, dissolved oxygen, fuel moisture, fuel temperature, precipitation, relative humidity, salinity, snow depth,  stream flow, stream gauge height, turbidity, water level, water temperature, wave height and direction, wind speed and direction, and acidity (pH).

sensorFilters.label: Pacific Islands Region
sensorFilters.description:
The Pacific Islands study region includes 25 island locations in the tropical Pacific west of 150° W that were divided into six regions based on proximity and similarity of general atmospheric patterns: Western, Marianas, Central, Northeast, Eastern Equatorial, and Southern regions. The Western region contains the islands of Palau and Yap in the Federated States of Micronesia. The Marianas region comprises Asuncion, Saipan, and Guam. The Central region is the largest, with Wake in the north, Chuuk, Kosrae, and Pohnpei in the Federated States of Micronesia, and Enewetak, Bikini, and Majuro in the Republic of the Marshall Islands. The Northeast region contains the Big Island of Hawaii, Molokai, Kauai, Midway, Johnston Atoll, and the Northwest Hawaiian Islands. The Eastern Equatorial region contains Palmyra, Kingman Reef, Howland, and Jarvis in the Pacific Remote Island Area. Finally, the Southern region encompasses two locations: American Samoa and Rose Atoll in the South Pacific Ocean.

Waves in the Western Tropical Pacific (WTP) are generally larger and more energetic during boreal winter than during other seasons. Swell generated by northern hemisphere extratropical cyclones dominates the extreme wave climate of the WTP during boreal and winters and summers. Boreal winter waves are generally the largest in the region each year, except for the Southern islands, where waves are largest during the boreal summer. These waves can traverse more than 4000 km within the basin, delivering energy from mid-latitude cyclones to islands near the equator. During boreal summer, waves generated by easterly trade winds dominate the swell-wave spectrum in the eastern half of the study area. Waves generated in the southern hemisphere characterize larger swell waves in the western half of the region during the boreal summer. Easterly trade winds dominate atmospheric circulation and surface winds within the region throughout most of the year. However, the strongest winds in the region are the result of tropical cyclones and other storm systems. The northeast quadrant of the study area receives strong winds and large waves from mid-latitude storms during boreal winter, despite the influence of the trades. Extreme winds and waves in the western half of the study area are mainly from typhoons and mid-latitude extra-tropical cyclones.

Two primary island types are found within this region: volcanic ?high? islands and low-lying atoll islands. Though most high islands, such as the Mariana and Main Hawaiian Islands, have high mean elevations (10s?1000s of m), their harbors, population centers, and infrastructure are generally concentrated along the coast within a few meters of sea level. These low-lying areas are vulnerable to large wave events. Many high islands in the tropical Pacific have fringing reefs along their coasts that function as breakwaters for incident waves, protecting coastal areas from larger waves and reducing wave-driven flooding. Atoll islands, such as the Marshall or Northwestern Hawaiian Islands, are low-lying carbonate islands on atoll reefs that generally have mean elevations of less than 2?3 m above sea level. They have high population densities and represent most of the inhabited landmass in the tropical Pacific. Due to their low elevations, many atoll islands are vulnerable to wave-driven flooding, shoreline erosion, and damage to habitats and infrastructure.

sensorFilters.description: The U.S. Geological Survey (USGS) Oceanographic Time-Series Measurements Database contains oceanographic observations made as part of studies designed to increase understanding of sediment transport processes and associated dynamics. The measurements were collected by investigators at the USGS Woods Hole Science Center (WHSC) and colleagues, beginning in 1975. Most of the field experiments were carried out on the U.S. continental shelf and slope.

sensorFilters.label: West Coast Region
sensorFilters.description:
The U.S. West Coast study region extends from 47.8600ºN to 32.4030ºN and includes Pacific Ocean waters offshore of Washington, Oregon, and California. Waves along the U.S. West Coast and offshore of the continental shelf are dominated by gravity waves from the North Pacific basin. Highest waves are seen during boreal fall and winter in response to mid-latitude North Pacific cyclones, Eastern Pacific tropical storms, and local winds. Extreme events have been linked to the Aleutian Low and other North Pacific atmospheric patterns such as the El Niño-Southern Oscillation. Swell and intermediate period waves with peak spectral wave periods greater than 6 seconds dominate the wave energy spectrum throughout the year, especially during boreal winter when swell can be more than five times greater than local sea energy. During boreal spring and summer, wave conditions are typically driven by prevailing northwesterly winds and southern hemisphere storms. Wave energy from southern ocean swell is particularly relevant along the Southern California coast where some south facing beaches are negatively impacted by long-period high waves from the south.

The continental shelf along the U.S. West Coast is relatively narrow and thus provides little dissipation of energy prior to waves reaching the shore. Within the Southern California Bight, the presence of an island chain and complex nearshore bathymetry significantly alters the deep-water wave climate by intercepting and reorienting wave energy, resulting in non-uniform wave energy distributions along this section of coast. With the exception of the Farallon Islands offshore of San Francisco Bay, only small islands and rock outcrops exist along the remaining open coast of California and the Pacific Northwest (Oregon and Washington). The interface between the Pacific Ocean and land is characterized by several different landforms such as cliffs, marine terraces, rocky shores, wide dissipative beaches, narrow steep beaches, estuaries, lagoons, and built infrastructure. Development along certain sections of the coast is extensive, particularly in California where more than 25 million people reside in coastal counties. Washington and Oregon coastal counties each host more than 4.6 million and 0.6 million inhabitants, respectively. Major transportation corridors and other critical infrastructure such as oil, natural gas, nuclear energy facilities, water and wastewater treatment plants, major ports, schools, and hospitals are found along the coast. Furthermore, cultural and ecological resources are extensive and offer a wide range of recreational and tourism opportunities. Large sections of low-lying areas are vulnerable to flooding, whereas other highly-valued areas are susceptible to coastal erosion. The coincidence of high waves with astronomic high tides (up to 3.3 m), month-long elevated sea levels associated with ENSO events (up to 0.5 m), and / or storm surge (up to 1.4 m) combined with rising sea level increases the likelihood that more wave energy will reach exposed beaches, sea cliffs, coastal developments, and other vulnerable coastal assets.

sensorFilters.label: West Coast Sensors
sensorFilters.description: The west coast real-time sensor catalog compiles current meteorologic and oceanographic data for the east coast from real-time in situ sensors. These include weather stations, stream gauges, webcam images, moorings, etc. Measurements and predictions include air temperature, air pressure, conductivity, water currents, water level, ground temperature, precipitation, humidity, salinity, snow depth, snow water equivalent, stream flow, stream gauge height, tides, waves, wind, and acidity (pH).
